After the 1971 season, the Washington Senators moved to become the Texas Rangers.
The Montreal Expos were relocated to Washington, becoming the Nationals.
Approval was granted by Major League Baseball owners, pending conditions outlined in the Baseball Stadium Agreement.
The city of Washington faced challenges in financing the new stadium, but ultimately secured public funding.
The Nationals made their debut against the New York Mets, with plans for a temporary home at RFK Stadium.
Despite obstacles from Orioles owner Peter Angelos, the Nationals' relocation to Washington was finalized, marking a historic moment in baseball.
